I don't think that most of the people often characterized as anti-American truly deserve that label.  Most folks discussing our previous conduct in the Middle East, good or bad, are just trying to make sense of the situation and understand the events that have led up to it.  It's true that we have sent aid to the region many, many times.  It's true that we've done our best to stop violence there and preserve human life.  It's also true that we've supported violent dicators and fanatics in order to maintain a political climate that some felt would be to our advantage.  We are not monsters, by any means.  Bin Laden is wrong in thinking this.  That doesn't make us angels though, and to refuse to accept this is arrogant.  I'm glad some folks are aware of the facts, and while I don't believe that a peaceful solution is possible I respect the opinions of those who do.  This is part of what makes our country a better one than Afghanistan.  Our diversity is our power, it is what divides us from single-minded fanatics like Bin Laden and his followers.<br>
Ironically enough, despite my generally liberal tendencies I have to say I'm impressed with the way the Bush administration has handled this.  They've learned from the millitary fuckups of Clinton and Bush Sr., and seem to genuinely want to do the right thing.  Props to them. <p>Arikel Callistrae <BR>
